-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - June 30
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Sun Jun 29, 2014 10:02PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 30 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- Lawmakers have urged the regulator of the controversial Mandatory Provident Fund to reduce fees on a wider range of funds and provide better protection for the 2.5 million employees in the scheme. (http://bit.ly/UZyMLN) -- Four men demonstrated their opposition to the Occupy Central civil disobedience movement on Sunday with some civil disobedience of their own - jumping off the pier at Tsim Sha Tsui Clock Tower into Victoria Harbour. (http://bit.ly/1pDbOI2) -- Two Taiwanese activists who plan to join tomorrow's rally in Hong Kong were refused entry on Sunday, raising accusations of political motives. (http://bit.ly/1k3HcYe)  THE STANDARD -- Sales of new flats continue to be brisk. New World Development <0017.HK> and Wheelock's <0020.HK> Grand Austin sold 131 flats on Sunday, ahead of the release of 256 units from Sino Land's <0083.HK> Mayfair By The Sea in Tai Po on Monday. (http://bit.ly/1lqyEuc) -- Seven companies open retail books on Monday targeting nearly HK$5 billion ($645 million). Of which, China Shengmu Organic Milk is seeking to raise up to HK$1.31 billion for its Hong Kong initial public offering and mattress maker Sinomax aims to raise up to HK$1.07 billion. (http://bit.ly/1vlHtuN) -- Central government auditors in China recently reported that domestic gold enterprises had taken out 94.4 billion yuan ($15.18 billion) worth of illegal loans. On most occasions, the wrongdoing involved using the same gold as collateral to take out several loans. (http://bit.ly/1mLoOrU)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- The total number of new listings on the Hong Kong stock exchange was at 48 during the first six months of 2014, the highest in 10 years.   HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Infrastructure machinery manufacturer Lonking Holdings Ltd <3339.HK> said it has agreed to sell an industrial site in China's Zhengzhou for 254 million yuan ($40.85 million).